      Tax structuring
   =20
 =20
A  basic rule of U.S. income tax is that a business pays tax on its net inc=
ome, but a person pays tax on her gross income. A business takes its revenu=
e, subtracts its expenses, and pays tax on the difference; business expense=
s are tax-deductible. A person takes her paycheck and pays taxes on that; p=
ersonal expenses are not tax-deductible.That is just the basic rule, though=
, and there are many exceptions. For instance there is a long list of perso=
nal expenses =E2=80=94=C2=A0mortgage interest and charitable donations are =
some big ones =E2=80=94=C2=A0that are more or less tax-deductible; you subt=
ract them from your income to arrive at your taxable income. For a long tim=
e, state and local taxes (=E2=80=9CSALT=E2=80=9D) were on that list; you co=
uld deduct them from your income in computing your federal tax liability. I=
n 2017, Congress changed that, capping the SALT deduction at $10,000. This =
is bad for high-income taxpayers in high-tax states, like, for instance, la=
w-firm partners in New York, who now have to pay federal taxes on a larger =
gross income and so pay more in taxes. It is also arguably bad for those hi=
gh-tax states: Income there is now taxed twice, as it were, so at some marg=
in those states will face pressure to lower taxes and reduce services, or h=
igh-income people might move away to lower-tax states.And so there is an in=
centive for tax structuring. The states want to continue collecting taxes f=
rom the high-income taxpayers, but both the states and the taxpayers would =
prefer for those taxes to remain deductible for federal tax purposes. The t=
axpayers say to the states =E2=80=9Cboy we=E2=80=99d like to pay you these =
taxes but state taxes are no longer deductible on our personal tax returns,=
 is there something you can do?=E2=80=9D And there is!From my brief concept=
ual overview there are two obvious paths to explore. One is: Call state and=
 local taxes something else, something that=C2=A0remains=C2=A0deductible. T=
he most straightforward=C2=A0move here is to call them =E2=80=9Ccharitable =
deductions.=E2=80=9D[1] Something like:=09The state charges income taxes.=
=09The state sets up a charity to fund state government, and you can donate=
 to the charity.=09Any donations to the state charity fund get a state tax =
credit (not a deduction): If you donate $20,000 to the charity, your state =
tax payable (not your state taxable=C2=A0income) goes down by $1,000.=09Ins=
tead of paying $20,000 of state taxes, you donate $20,000 to the fund and p=
ay zero in state taxes.=09You have a $20,000 charitable deduction for your =
federal taxes.That=E2=80=99s a good one, we discussed it a couple of times =
in  2017 and  2018,=C2=A0and people (that is, states) definitely tried it. =
It did not really work, though; the Internal Revenue Service concluded=C2=
=A0that you don=E2=80=99t get the charitable deduction for that $20,000, be=
cause you got something of value (the tax credit) for your donation.=C2=A0T=
he other path is a bit subtler[2]: Call the state and local taxes =E2=80=9C=
state and local taxes,=E2=80=9D but instead of making=C2=A0people=C2=A0pay =
them (people=E2=80=99s expenses are not generally deductible from their fed=
eral income taxes), make=C2=A0businesses=C2=A0pay them (state and local tax=
es, like other business expenses,=C2=A0remain deductible for businesses). I=
t=E2=80=99s a bit tricky doing that in the general case,[3] but here=E2=80=
=99s a Wall Street Journal article about one version that apparently works:=
New York business owners are saving billions of dollars in taxes by using a=
 state-approved system for sidestepping the $10,000 federal cap on state an=
d local tax deductions.Owners of closely held businesses paid the state $11=
 billion in pass-through entity taxes by the end of 2021, according to the =
state=E2=80=99s Department of Tax and Finance. Pass-through businesses usua=
lly don=E2=80=99t pay income taxes directly but pass income and deductions =
through to their owners=E2=80=99 individual returns.By paying New York=E2=
=80=99s new pass-through entity tax, those business owners shifted their st=
ate income taxes from their individual tax returns=E2=80=94where the cap wo=
uld pinch them=E2=80=94to their business filings, where the cap doesn=E2=80=
=99t affect them.The total represents about one-sixth of New York=E2=80=99s=
 projected personal income tax revenue for the fiscal year ending March 31.=
 The result: If those business owners had an average federal tax rate of 32=
%, they would be saving more than $3 billion. =E2=80=A6Some of New York=E2=
=80=99s largest law, financial and accounting firms routed their partners=
=E2=80=99 income through the state=E2=80=99s workaround, which took effect =
last year. Nearly 96,000 filers used the program, the tax department said.=
=E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s a big number,=E2=80=9D said James Wetzler, a former=
 New York tax commissioner. The take-up is much greater than other workarou=
nds, he said, including a program that lets employers pay federally deducti=
ble payroll taxes to help their employees have lower income taxes. That pro=
gram had 328 users in 2021, according to the state. The Trump administratio=
n nixed another workaround that relied on people making charitable contribu=
tions in lieu of taxes.=C2=A0Basically if you are a partner at a law firm a=
nd your share of the firm=E2=80=99s profits is $1 million, you have persona=
l income of $1 million: The law firm is a =E2=80=9Cpass-through entity=E2=
=80=9D for tax purposes, and does not normally pay taxes itself; the partne=
rs treat its income as their income and pay taxes on it. But under the new =
New York system, the partnership can pay your share of the state income tax=
es, which is a business expense for the partnership and so reduces your inc=
ome. If your state income tax would be $100,000, the partnership pays it, a=
nd you have $900,000 of taxable income. You=E2=80=99ve paid the state taxes=
 out of the business=E2=80=99s income, before it became income=C2=A0to you,=
 so you effectively get to deduct it from your federal taxes:Details vary b=
y state, but here=E2=80=99s generally how the workarounds operate. States i=
mpose taxes=E2=80=94often optional=E2=80=94on pass-through entities such as=
 partnerships and S corporations, a tax designation for certain closely hel=
d businesses. Those taxes are paid and get subtracted before income flows t=
o business owners, effectively creating an unlimited deduction.The laws use=
 tax credits or other mechanisms to absolve owners of individual income-tax=
 liabilities from business income. Thus, they satisfy state income-tax obli=
gations without generating income-tax deductions subject to the federal cap=
.Good trade! In general I think of tax structuring as having two competing =
sides:=09Governments, who try to write and enforce tax rules in ways that a=
re hard to game, and=09Sophisticated taxpayers, who try to game the rules a=
nyway.And there are various things that you can say about that competition,=
 and about which side pays its advisers more, etc., but the point is here t=
hat you have tax-code writers and taxpayers teaming up to minimize the taxp=
ayers=E2=80=99=C2=A0other=C2=A0taxes. A nice little synergy.
