      Web3 Stuff
   =20
 =20
Yesterday I wrote about Web3 and I wanted to follow up with a few things he=
re. First I should=C2=A0link to two other excellent newsletters that wrote =
about similar Web3 issues, Can Duruk at the Margins=C2=A0and Ben Thompson a=
t Stratechery last week=C2=A0and again yesterday.Second, in writing about t=
he practical centralization of Web3, I discussed ExcelCoin,=C2=A0my pretend=
 cryptocurrency that I keep on a list in Microsoft Excel. =E2=80=9CIf you w=
ant to buy some of my quadrillion ExcelCoins, send me an email,=E2=80=9D I =
wrote, like an idiot;=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI will make a market at $0.99 bid / $1.=
01 offered.=E2=80=9D A footnote to that sentence said =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99=
t actually=E2=80=9D send me an email, but who reads footnotes. Anyway I got=
 a number of emails asking to buy ExcelCoins. The number is large enough th=
at it was not convenient for me to respond to each email individually, sorr=
y, and yet it was also small enough that I am not planning to quit my job t=
o live off sales of ExcelCoin. I believe I have orders for 393.01 ExcelCoin=
s, for which I could get about $396.94.[4] In a sense that=E2=80=99s a pret=
ty good rate for typing a few numbers into a spreadsheet, but I worry about=
 scalability.Also, in writing about ExcelCoin, I mentioned that the technol=
ogy (me typing in Excel) could be extended to track non-fungible tokens, no=
t just fungible coins. (One ExcelCoin bidder also=C2=A0asked for an ExcelNF=
T of =E2=80=9Ca picture of a rocket=E2=80=9D though we did not talk price.)=
 Apparently Roy Keyes had already implemented a very similar idea, called C=
SVChain; the way it works is that you send Keyes an email asking to buy one=
 of the NFTs listed on the site, and if you agree on a trade he updates the=
 CSV file listing the owners of the NFTs. =E2=80=9CAll transactions are app=
ended to the CSV file using the echo command and the >> operator, making th=
e CSVCHAIN immutable. The CSVCHAIN is held in cold storage on this=C2=A0USB=
=C2=A0drive to ensure its security.=E2=80=9D This is a good joke! We had a =
little exchange on Twitter and now I seem to own a CSVChain NFT named Scorp=
 Scorpy Scorp.[5] I would include a picture of it here but I have no idea a=
bout its copyright status!Finally,=C2=A0one technical point. Yesterday, aft=
er joking about ExcelCoin,=C2=A0I wrote:On the other hand millions and mill=
ions of people own U.S. dollars,=C2=A0which means precisely=C2=A0that some =
bank has a list and there is an entry for them on that list. It=E2=80=99s p=
robably not in Excel, but same basic idea: The bank has a list of dollars i=
n its accounts, the list is not kept via any sort of consensus mechanism or=
 blockchain or whatever; the bank just keeps the list using, uh,=C2=A0Cobol=
.=C2=A0A reader pointed out that really there is=C2=A0a consensus mechanism=
, insofar as banks usually keep=C2=A0multiple copies=C2=A0of the list in di=
fferent systems and have some mechanism for making sure they agree. This is=
 about redundancy and resiliency, not about decentralization =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the=C2=A0bank=C2=A0keeps all the lists =E2=80=94=C2=A0but, still: consen=
sus mechanism. The actual dollar financial system is better run than ExcelC=
oin.
