te taxes for me, I=E2=80=99d presumably have additional federal taxable inc=
ome for that amount. To the extent a state charges personal income tax, let=
ting a business pay the tax for its employees doesn=E2=80=99t really help. =
What you need is to recharacterize the tax as something other than personal=
 income tax. Charging businesses payroll taxes (instead of charging individ=
uals income taxes) is promising, but complicated. Charging *pass-through* b=
usinesses an income tax on income that would otherwise be passed through to=
 their partners is promising and relatively straightforward.[4] Here I am c=
ounting people who sent emails or tweets like =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll buy 20 =
at the offer, what=E2=80=99s your Venmo,=E2=80=9D not people who sent email=
s or tweets like =E2=80=9Chow do I buy ExcelCoins,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cyou=
 should sell them for real, you=E2=80=99d make a lot of money,=E2=80=9D or =
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d like a billion.=E2=80=9D Some people sent in bids with=
 higher limits than my $1.01 offer; I count those as bids at $1.01 (i.e. I =
assumed that my offer would not move despite the demand). Some people seem =
to have bid $1.00, technically below my offer, but I counted those because,=
 I mean, this is all fake. Some people were flexible on size; I used the ma=
ximum size that they specified. A few people offered to exchange ExcelCoins=
 for various coins they had invented and kept on their own spreadsheets (or=
, in one case, in their own memory; =E2=80=9CIt's very fast=E2=80=9D); I di=
d not count these unless they also offered dollars as an alternative. And, =
yes, one person emailed asking to buy 0.01 ExcelCoins, explicitly to pump u=
p the market cap of ExcelCoin: If someone buys 0.01 for $0.01, then my rema=
ining 999,999,999,999,999.99 ExcelCoins should be worth $999,999,999,999,99=
9.99, making me the world=E2=80=99s richest person, technically. Oh, also, =
fun fact about that last sentence: I went into my Excel ledger of ExcelCoin=
s, where I have written down that I own 1,000,000,000,000,000.000000 ExcelC=
oins, and I took that number and subtracted 0.01, and Excel told me that I=
=E2=80=99d have 1,000,000,000,000,000.000000 ExcelCoins left. My own math d=
oes not agree with Excel, whoops. It is possible that ExcelCoin is too big =
a project to keep in Excel.[5] To be clear, I did not send him money for Sc=
orp Scorpy Scorp, I did not ask for it, and =E2=80=94=C2=A0despite its list=
ing on his site with a purported minimum price of $7,117 =E2=80=94=C2=A0I a=
m not looking to sell it. I assume that he, and I, are joking about all of =
this, and that nothing of value has been exchanged. I do think that the com=
bination of (1) huge valuations for=C2=A0ephemeral zero-cost=C2=A0nonsense =
and (2) air-dropping can create some odd issues of journalistic (and other)=
 ethics, though. Are you sure that Scorp Scorpy Scorp *isn=E2=80=99t* worth=
 $7,117? If you minted an NFT of, like, spinning neon text saying =E2=80=9C=
BRIBE=E2=80=9D and burned it to the chair of the Securities and Exchange Co=
mmission, is that a thing?
