om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Tax structuring</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/26331966.267646/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMDkvc2VjLWdvZXMtYWZ0ZXItYW5hbHlzdC1mb3Jlc2hhZ=
G93aW5nP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTEyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nv=
dXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDExMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB18151a2f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> basic rule</a> of U.S. income t=
ax is that a business pays tax on its net income, but a person pays tax on =
her gross income. A business takes its revenue, subtracts its expenses, and=
 pays tax on the difference; business expenses are tax-deductible. A person=
 takes her paycheck and pays taxes on that; personal expenses are not tax-d=
eductible.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is just the basic rule, tho=
ugh, and there are many exceptions. For instance there is a long list of pe=
rsonal expenses =E2=80=94=C2=A0mortgage interest and charitable donations a=
re some big ones =E2=80=94=C2=A0that are more or less tax-deductible; you s=
ubtract them from your income to arrive at your taxable income. For a long =
time, state and local taxes (=E2=80=9CSALT=E2=80=9D) were on that list; you=
 could deduct them from your income in computing your federal tax liability=
. In 2017, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2633196=
6.267646/aHR0cHM6Ly90YXhmb3VuZGF0aW9uLm9yZy9zYWx0LWRlZHVjdGlvbi1jYXAtcmVwZW=
FsLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB088d1fe3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Congress changed that</a>, =
capping the SALT deduction at $10,000. This is bad for high-income taxpayer=
s in high-tax states, like, for instance, law-firm partners in New York, wh=
o now have to pay federal taxes on a larger gross income and so pay more in=
 taxes. It is also arguably bad for those high-tax states: Income there is =
now taxed twice, as it were, so at some margin those states will face press=
ure to lower taxes and reduce services, or high-income people might move aw=
ay to lower-tax states.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so there is an =
incentive for tax structuring. The states want to continue collecting taxes=
 from the high-income taxpayers, but both the states and the taxpayers woul=
d prefer for those taxes to remain deductible for federal tax purposes. The=
 taxpayers say to the states =E2=80=9Cboy we=E2=80=99d like to pay you thes=
e taxes but state taxes are no longer deductible on our personal tax return=
s, is there something you can do?=E2=80=9D And there is!</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">From my brief conceptual overview there are two obvious paths=
 to explore. One is: Call state and local taxes something else, something t=
hat=C2=A0<em>remains=C2=A0</em>deductible. The most straightforward=C2=A0mo=
ve here is to call them =E2=80=9Ccharitable deductions.=E2=80=9D[1] Somethi=
ng like:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; marg=
in: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The state charges income =
taxes.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The state sets up a charity=
 to fund state government, and you can donate to the charity.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Any donations to the state charity fund get a s=
tate tax <em>credit </em>(not a deduction): If you donate $20,000 to the ch=
arity, your state <em>tax payable</em> (not your state taxable=C2=A0<em>inc=
ome</em>) goes down by $1,000.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Ins=
tead of paying $20,000 of state taxes, you donate $20,000 to the fund and p=
ay zero in state taxes.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have a=
 $20,000 charitable deduction for your federal taxes.</li></ol><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s a good one, we discussed it a couple of tim=
es in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26331966.267=
646/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMTItMDg=
vYml0Y29pbi1zd2luZ3MtYW5kLXRheC1nbGl0Y2hlcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTExMjJfTU9ORVlTVF=
VGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAxM=
TEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB609beb07" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> 2017</a> and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
6331966.267646/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MTgtMDEtMDMvbWlmaWQtaWktcnVsZXMtbWlnaHQtbWVhbi1sZXNzLWVtYWlsP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA=
xMTEyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJn=
V0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDExMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB954c6f15" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> 2018</a>,=C2=A0and people (that is, states) definitel=
y tried it. It did not really work, though; the Internal Revenue Service <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26331966.267646/aHR0=
cHM6Ly90YXhmb3VuZGF0aW9uLm9yZy9pcnMtc2FsdC13b3JrYXJvdW5kLWNoYXJpdGFibGUtZGV=
kdWN0aW9uLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd8f630a1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">concluded</a>=C2=A0t=
hat you don=E2=80=99t get the charitable deduction for that $20,000, becaus=
e you got something of value (the tax credit) for your donation.=C2=A0</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other path is a bit subtler[2]: Call the st=
ate and local taxes =E2=80=9Cstate and local taxes,=E2=80=9D but instead of=
 making=C2=A0<em>people=C2=A0</em>pay them (people=E2=80=99s expenses are n=
ot generally deductible from their federal income taxes), make=C2=A0<em>bus=
inesses=C2=A0</em>pay them (state and local taxes, like other business expe=
nses,=C2=A0remain deductible for businesses). It=E2=80=99s a bit tricky doi=
ng that in the general case,[3] but here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26331966.267646/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS=
9hcnRpY2xlcy9uZXcteW9yay1idXNpbmVzcy1vd25lcnMtc2lkZXN0ZXAtYmlsbGlvbnMtaW4tZ=
mVkZXJhbC10YXhlcy13aXRoLXN0YXRlcy1oZWxwLTExNjQxODQ2NDM1P21vZD1ocF9saXN0YV9w=
b3Mz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB28f6c786" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a Wall Street Journal artic=
le</a> about one version that apparently works:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">New York business owners are saving billions of dollars in=
 taxes by using a state-approved system for sidestepping the $10,000 federa=
l cap on state and local tax deductions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ow=
ners of closely held businesses paid the state $11 billion in pass-through =
entity taxes by the end of 2021, according to the state=E2=80=99s Departmen=
t of Tax and Finance. Pass-through businesses usually don=E2=80=99t pay inc=
ome taxes directly but pass income and deductions through to their owners=
=E2=80=99 individual returns.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By paying New=
 York=E2=80=99s new pass-through entity tax, those business owners shifted =
their state income taxes from their individual tax returns=E2=80=94where th=
e cap would pinch them=E2=80=94to their business filings, where the cap doe=
sn=E2=80=99t affect them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The total represe=
nts about one-sixth of New York=E2=80=99s projected personal income tax rev=
enue for the fiscal year ending March 31. The result: If those business own=
ers had an average federal tax rate of 32%, they would be saving more than =
$3 billion. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some of New York=E2=
=80=99s largest law, financial and accounting firms routed their partners=
=E2=80=99 income through the state=E2=80=99s workaround, which took effect =
last year. Nearly 96,000 filers used the program, the tax department said.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s a big number,=E2=80=
=9D said James Wetzler, a former New York tax commissioner. The take-up is =
much greater than other workarounds, he said, including a program that lets=
 employers pay federally deductible payroll taxes to help their employees h=
ave lower income taxes. That program had 328 users in 2021, according to th=
e state. The Trump administration nixed another workaround that relied on p=
eople making charitable contributions in lieu of taxes.=C2=A0</p></blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically if you are a partner at a law fir=
m and your share of the firm=E2=80=99s profits is $1 million, you have pers=
onal income of $1 million: The law firm is a =E2=80=9Cpass-through entity=
=E2=80=9D for tax purposes, and does not normally pay taxes itself; the par=
tners treat its income as their income and pay taxes on it. But under the n=
ew New York system, the partnership can pay your share of the state income =
taxes, which is a business expense for the partnership and so reduces your =
income. If your state income tax would be $100,000, the partnership pays it=
, and you have $900,000 of taxable income. You=E2=80=99ve paid the state ta=
xes out of the business=E2=80=99s income, before it became income=C2=A0to y=
ou, so you effectively get to deduct it from your federal taxes:</p><blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Details vary by state, but here=E2=80=99s=
 generally how the workarounds operate. States impose taxes=E2=80=94often o=
ptional=E2=80=94on pass-through entities such as partnerships and S corpora=
tions, a tax designation for certain closely held businesses. Those taxes a=
re paid and get subtracted before income flows to business owners, effectiv=
ely creating an unlimited deduction.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The la=
ws use tax credits or other mechanisms to absolve owners of individual inco=
me-tax liabilities from business income. Thus, they satisfy state income-ta=
x obligations without generating income-tax deductions subject to the feder=
al cap.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Good trade! In general=
 I think of tax structuring as having two competing sides:</p><ol style=3D"=
list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Governments, who try to write and enforce tax rule=
s in ways that are hard to game, and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">Sophisticated taxpayers, who try to game the rules anyway.</li></ol><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And there are various things that you can say abou=
t that competition, and about which side pays its advisers more, etc., but =
the point is here that you have tax-code writers and taxpayers teaming up t=
o minimize the taxpayers=E2=80=99=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>taxes. A nice li=
ttle synergy.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cellpaddi=
ng=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center">
