om regular retail investors and mutual funds and so forth. Other companies =
are private, meaning they don=E2=80=99t have to publish much information, b=
ut are legally limited to raising=C2=A0money mostly from =E2=80=9Caccredite=
d investors,=E2=80=9D basically rich people and institutions.=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Companies start out being private.=C2=A0Historical=
ly one reason that companies switched from being private to being public is=
 that they wanted to: Being public is annoying, what with all of the detail=
ed financial reports and shareholder lawsuits, but there=E2=80=99s more mon=
ey in public markets than in private ones, so if you wanted to raise a lot =
of money you=E2=80=99d go public. Another reason that companies switched fr=
om being private to being public, though, is that they had to: U.S. securit=
ies laws had a rule saying that a company with more than 500 shareholders h=
as to register its securities publicly, file reports, etc. The theory was b=
asically, you know, if you have 500 shareholders, you are not a closely hel=
d family company or anything; you are pretty public, so you might as well s=
end audited financial statements etc. to all those shareholders. And so if =
you were a private company and you got big enough and lasted long enough, y=
our stock would sort of leak out to more and more people: You=E2=80=99d hir=
e more employees and give them stock, your early investors would sell down =
their stock as its value went up, etc., until you ended up with more than 5=
00 holders and had to be public. (This is, for instance, a <a href=3D"https=
